A leader and organizer can make a huge difference. Look at Microsoft under Satya vs Ballmer. Satya is not writing code, but under his leadership, Microsofties are working on more impactful products, customers are getting more value, and the company is generating more cash. (5)

A founder/CEO is not necessarily the smartest, most hardworking person in the company. They are the creator and maintainer of the system (usually centered around an idea/product/strategy) that allows everyone else to thrive and produce their best work together. (4)

If a company creates more efficiency and value than the status quo (by creating something from nothing or generating economic opportunities), then the company becomes more valuable and the people who have ownership in the company can control how the surplus value is invested. (3)

Culture isnâ€™t solely shaped by the will and character of the people in the building but also by the incentives and systems of the industry in which the firm operates. When evaluating career choices, or designing company incentives, game theory can provide a useful framework (fin)

I notice that zero sum industries tend to have more zero sum internal cultures, but that does not necessarily have to be the case if the team deliberately designs internal incentives to be positive sum. (8)

Internal incentives can also be zero sum or positive sum. Eg Teams competing for budget allocation from a fixed pool vs creating budgets from first principles, stack ranking employees vs predetermined metrics for success etc. (7)

Other industries are more fundamentally zero sum. In many sectors of finance, when you win a deal, your competitor loses it. In politics, if youâ€™re elected into office, your opponent loses. As a result people may be less transparent or more likely to undermine others. (6)

The tech industry as a whole is focused on creating exponential value from fixed resources and new products/behaviors and thus has many positive sum characteristics. There are also zero sum scenarios in tech, which are more common as cos get larger (Uber vs Lyft, FB vs Snap) (5)

Working at growing startups can be a unique and refreshing experience in the corporate world because they are so positive sum. If you come up with an idea for a new feature that increases revenues and growth, the entire company is better off. (4)

Zero sum cultures tend to be more competitive and less cooperative as people view the success of others as a threat to their own success. Positive sum cultures tend to be cooperative and innovative as people are focused on growing the pie rather than fighting for slices. (3)

Whether a job or an industry is zero sum or positive sum has a huge impact on culture. In zero sum games, the success of one party comes directly at the expense of another. In contrast, in positive sum games, the success of one party can make all parties better off. (2)

7/ Looking back, I wish one of the scrappy hustlers took the reigns as head of marketing and fought hard for a seat at the table. I wish marketing remained more closely aligned with product. I wish we established /simple and clear areas of ownership and rules of engagement.

6/Instead, marketing rolled into either product or ops. The relationships between the orgs was strained. It wasnâ€™t clear if one was supporting the other or vice versa. This led to matrixed orgs across regions/businesses with duplication of effort and lack of clarity on objectives
5/ Uber didnâ€™t hire a CMO for many years. Marketing was a huge driver for growth and a large cost center, but there was never a seat for marketing at the senior leadership table.

4/ The early growth marketers didnâ€™t have fancy resumes, but were scrappy hustlers who found creative ways to get shit done. Many years of marketing experience didnâ€™t necessarily help for a company in hyper-growth creating new consumer behaviors.

3/ Uberâ€™s original marketing team was part of the growth team, a product org. Marketers, engineers, designers, data scientists worked side by side. This was extremely effective , but was hard to scale. Eventually, marketing needed to be spun out.

2/ Uber could not have grown exponentially without marketing. Period. The original Uber growth marketing team was the best of the best and are now founders, VPs (and VCs :P) at the next generation of startups.

Reading your replies, I notice many people equating valuation/stage with risk.   While often correlated, they are not the same. Risk is a function of product, traction, team, biz model etc. Valuation is a negotiation between a small group at a single point in time.

The real â€œunicornsâ€ for startup employees are the opportunities at companies that have really started to work, but have not yet raised a large growth round. Those are de-risked career-making opportunities. Uber right after UberX launched for example...

@adam_zethraeus Capital obviously is very important for growth, as we both know from Uber, but itâ€™s hard to isolate the impact due to many confounding variables. Leveraging capital to gain enough market leadership to unlock scale economies and network effects is a great strategy IMO

@JonahLupton All of those are very valid factors, but I would look at them from first principles rather than using valuation as a proxy. A startup could be cash flow positive and not need to raise money, so they wouldnt have a fancy valuation, but they would still be a great business.

@sgondala2 Ask about growth, retention, how they find their customers, the long term vision and team they have. Most startups are pretty open. Then do your own homework on the market, the problem theyâ€™re solving, competitors, incumbents, long term competitive advantage.

@sgondala2 I disagree about the likelihood to exit. If you are earlier, you have many more exit options that would still result in a good return for shareholders. When you have a very high valuation, your options are more limited to IPO or acquisition by a giant.

@sgondala2 Startups tend to be pretty open about their growth goals, the long term vision, the market they are tackling. While you might not get EBITDA margins, you can get a good sense of market, growth and team.
@magdalenakala When I was first joining Uber, I was a total n00b and has no idea what the difference was between the different VCs ğŸ˜‚ Ironic now, but I can empathize.

If youâ€™re an investor this sounds super obvious but Iâ€™ve actually lost candidates at portfolio cos because they wanted to join â€œunicorns.â€ Even if the unicorns were priced well ahead of the business. Joining A company at $300M vs $3B has an order of magnitude of upside difference

If youâ€™re looking to join a startup, you maximize upside when you join at a LOWER valuation, esp. when the business is hitting an inflection point.   Too many candidates gravitate to valuation as the most important metric. The higher the valuation, the lower your upside potential
